    bioFull: `Nadab had every advantage. He was Aaron's eldest son, which made him the presumptive next high priest of Israel. He was one of the seventy elders who went partway up Sinai with Moses and "saw the God of Israel" and ate and drank in the divine presence. He had a front-row seat to the establishment of Israel's worship. He watched his father receive the priestly garments. He was there when the glory of God filled the tabernacle. And then, in one of the most jarring scenes in the Pentateuch, he and his brother Abihu offered "strange fire" — unauthorized fire — before the Lord, and fire came out from God's presence and killed them both.

The text is deliberately spare about what exactly they did wrong. "Strange fire" or "unauthorized fire" is the only explanation given. Centuries of commentary have tried to fill the gap: Were they drunk? (The prohibition against priests drinking on duty immediately follows this story.) Did they use fire from a common source instead of the altar? Did they enter the Most Holy Place without permission? Did they improvise a ritual God hadn't commanded? The text refuses to specify, and that refusal is itself the point — they did something God hadn't authorized, and the consequences were immediate and lethal.

Think of it this way: imagine you're a new surgeon, and your father is the chief of surgery. You grew up around operating rooms. You've seen more procedures than anyone your age. And on one of your first solo cases, you improvise — you try a technique that wasn't in the protocol, maybe because you thought you knew better, maybe because you were showing off, maybe because you were careless. And someone dies on the table. The details of what Nadab did matter less than the principle: the sacred has protocols, and confidence is not the same as authorization.

What makes Nadab's story truly devastating is what it did to his father. Aaron, the high priest, watched his two sons die in the very tabernacle he served, and the text says he was silent. Moses told him, essentially, that God's holiness had been demonstrated, and Aaron held his peace. The grief was not given voice. The liturgy continued. The sacrifice schedule did not pause. And Nadab's body was carried out of the camp by his cousins.`,
