    faithJourney: `Nadab's faith journey is essentially a cautionary tale about the difference between exposure and formation. He was exposed to everything — the presence of God on Sinai, the ordination rituals, the glory filling the tabernacle. He had more spiritual experience than virtually anyone alive. And none of it was enough to prevent him from treating God's holiness casually. Exposure is not the same as reverence. Seeing is not the same as understanding.

What's particularly sobering about Nadab is that his story sits right at the beginning of Israel's formal worship life. The tabernacle was brand new. The priesthood had just been inaugurated. And the very first recorded priestly act after the consecration ceremony was a violation. Nadab's faith, whatever it looked like from the inside, produced behavior that the text describes as unauthorized. Whether he lacked fear, lacked attention, or lacked sobriety, what he lacked was the one thing his role demanded above all: the recognition that the sacred is not yours to improvise upon, no matter how close to it you grew up.`,
