    bioFull: `Abihu is always mentioned alongside Nadab, and that pairing raises a question the text doesn't answer: did they plan this together, or did one follow the other? The difference matters. If they conspired, it was a coordinated act of liturgical improvisation. If one initiated and the other followed, Abihu might represent something even more common and more dangerous than presumption — he might represent the person who goes along with a bad decision because someone he trusted was making it.

Abihu, like Nadab, had been on Sinai. He had seen God. He had been ordained alongside his father and brothers. He had every piece of information he needed to know better. But information and formation are different things. You can know all the rules and still not have the character to follow them when the moment comes. Abihu's story is the story of someone whose credentials outran his character — or whose loyalty to his brother outran his loyalty to the protocol.

The aftermath is where the story gets unbearable. Aaron was told not to mourn publicly. The priestly garments stayed on. The service continued. Moses explained it as God demonstrating holiness — "Among those who are near me I will be sanctified" — which is theologically coherent and emotionally brutal. Abihu was near God, and nearness without sanctity was lethal. His cousins carried his body out of the camp while his father stood in silence.

What lingers about Abihu is the unanswered question of agency. The text treats him and Nadab as equally culpable, but we don't know if he was equally initiating. Every group disaster has leaders and followers, and we're not told which Abihu was. What we're told is that both of them burned, which means that following someone into unauthorized territory carries the same consequence as leading them there. The fire didn't distinguish between architect and accomplice.`,
