    faithJourney: `Jephthah's daughter's faith, if we can call it that, is expressed in her response to her father: "You have opened your mouth to the Lord; do to me according to what has gone out of your mouth." She accepted a vow made to God as binding, even when it bound her. That acceptance has been read as admirable submission, as tragic internalized obligation, and as the response of someone who had no power to refuse. Probably it was all three. She believed the vow mattered. She believed God received it. And she believed her role was to honor it, even at the cost of everything she might have been.

But the two months on the mountains are where her faith becomes most visible and most painful. She asked for time. Not to escape, not to overturn the vow, but to grieve. She took her companions and she mourned her virginity — the life unlived, the family uncreated, the future that was already spoken for by words she didn't choose. Her faith held the paradox of believing in a God who receives vows and grieving the fact that this particular vow consumed her. She didn't resolve the paradox. She lived inside it for two months, on the mountains, with her friends, weeping. And then she came back. The annual commemoration by Israel's daughters suggests that the other women in the community knew something irreducible had been lost and refused to let it be forgotten.`,
