    bioBrief: 'One of Eli\'s two corrupt sons who treated the sacrificial system as a personal buffet, slept with women at the tabernacle entrance, and died the day the ark of God was captured.',
    bioFull: `Phinehas son of Eli shares a name with one of the most zealous priests in Israel's history — Phinehas son of Eleazar, who stopped a plague by driving a spear through an Israelite man and a Midianite woman in the act. The contrast is deliberate and devastating. The earlier Phinehas was rewarded with an everlasting covenant of priesthood. This Phinehas destroyed the priesthood he inherited.

The text calls Phinehas and his brother Hophni "worthless men" who "did not know the Lord." That phrase — "did not know the Lord" — is theologically loaded. They served in the tabernacle. They performed the sacrifices. They wore the garments. And they did not know God. Their religion was all mechanics and no relationship. They treated the sacrificial system as their personal commissary, sending servants to fork meat out of the pot before the fat was burned for God, and threatening violence against anyone who objected. They were stealing from the worshippers and from God simultaneously.

They also "lay with the women who were serving at the entrance to the tent of meeting." The sexual exploitation of women in a place of worship by the men entrusted with that worship is one of the ugliest patterns in human religious history, and it starts here. Phinehas used his position to access vulnerable women in a sacred space. He turned the door of the tabernacle into a site of predation.

Eli knew about all of it. He confronted his sons, but the text says they wouldn't listen, "for it was the will of the Lord to put them to death." That's a terrifying sentence — not because it suggests God made them sin, but because it suggests their sin had reached a point where repentance was no longer available. The Israelites went to war against the Philistines, lost the first battle, and then brought the ark of the covenant to the front lines like a talisman. Phinehas and Hophni accompanied it. The Philistines captured the ark, killed thirty thousand Israelite soldiers, and killed both of Eli's sons. When a messenger brought the news to Eli, the old man fell backward off his chair, broke his neck, and died.

Phinehas's wife, pregnant and in labor when the news arrived, named her son Ichabod — "the glory has departed from Israel" — because the ark was taken and her husband and father-in-law were dead. And then she died too. The entire priestly family was destroyed in a single day.`,
    modernParallel: `Phinehas is the pastor's kid who becomes a pastor himself, not out of calling but out of access — who uses the trust and the position to enrich himself and exploit the vulnerable. He's the executive at the charity who skims donations for personal expenses and harasses the staff, knowing that the institution's reputation will protect him for a while. He's the second-generation anything who inherits a sacred trust and treats it as a personal asset. Specifically, Phinehas represents the corruption that happens when someone grows up inside a system of holiness and learns to work the system without ever being changed by the holiness. If you've ever seen a religious institution implode because the leaders were using it for personal gain and sexual exploitation, you've seen the house of Eli collapse in real time.`,
